'''Robbing Peter to pay Paul''' is an English [[idiom]] referring to taking money from one party to pay one's debt to another.

A modern example is [[check kiting]].

The expression refers to times before the [[Reformation]] when Church taxes had to be paid to [[St. Paul's]] church in [[London]] and to [[St. Peter's]] church in [[Rome]]; the reference is to the neglect of the Peter tax to obtain money to pay the Paul tax.{{Fact|date=October 2007}}

